Title: You Asked for Perfect
Author: Laura  Silverman
My Review:
*1.99999/5

warning: this review is a fucking mess.

i have so many things to say about this book but they piss me the hell off so idk how comprehensive or comprehensible this review will be. i'm probably gonna make a rant review video so i can properly complain about everything i hate about it. :D

but for now here's some general thoughts. i'm basically just ranting so good luck to whoever's reading this.

ariel is the most annoying main character in existence. he's prospective valedictorian at his school, and he has the neurosis and irritating tryhard personality to show for it. he's literally every person i hated in high school, including myself. he's completely obsessed with grades and takes every AP class he can get his hands on in order to boost his GPA (since APs are weighted higher). whenever something happens that he perceives can threaten his prospective valedictorian status, his mentality and actions regarding it is borderline psychotic. his main competitor is this girl named pari, and in order to beat her out of the valedictorian spot he took this online AP comp sci class and purposefully didn't tell her about it until the sign-up date had passed. his thoughts regarding it? "i'm not going to apologize for being the one to come out on top."
then one page later he fails a quiz and is trying to keep it on the DL because then pari will continue to "keep her guard down" and not try harder knowing it's possible to overtake him for the valedictorian spot.
he's also judgy af towards amir (his later love interest) for no good reason. he thinks amir thinks he's better than everybody for some reason, even tho amir hasn't done anything except be antisocial at social gatherings. at one point he sees amir wearing a ravenclaw shirt and he's like "he WOULD identify as ravenclaw, the most pretentious of the hogwarts hosues." bitch??? a) literally what has he done to you??? and b) have you met yourself??? (btw: later amir says he thinks ariel's a gryffinclaw which is hilarious to me bc this man is definitely a slytherin. ((no shade to slytherins he does not speak for y'all.)) he's manipulative af and would literally do anything to be valedictorian. literally textbook slytherin with his level of ambitiousness and relentlessness.)
anyway, ariel's only personality trait is being an annoying tryhard little bitch... and liking sour candy. he's sooooo quirky XD!1!!!

eh i don't feel like talking about this book anymore so lemme just jot down some last few thoughts.

there's a ridiculous number of harry potter references. like, way too many. there's also 1 mention of t*mblr and THE LITERAL PHRASE "I SHIP IT" in this book. i am in physical pain. what is this, 2012?

ariel ends up kind of realizing what he did was shitty (mostly bc all his friends started hating him for being a dick and only caring about himself/school) and realizes ~grades aren't everything~. but does that make up for the torture i endured for the other 80% of this book? no. the book is average at best in terms of plot/characters/interesting-ness. all the takeaways and lessons we're supposed to garner are pretty straightforward and the same as any other book with the similar premise. but the fact that ariel is super annoying makes it so much worse.

so does this book rly deserve 1 star? eh. it'd probably get a 2 if i was feeling generous, but i'm not. so fuck you.

Title: A Good Girl's Guide to Murder (A Good Girl's Guide to Murder, #1)
Author: Holly  Jackson
My Review:
honestly this book probs wasn't the best quality-wise but i enjoyed it a lot sooooo

the negative reviews i've seen all have the same complaints, and they're completely valid. the main character, pippa, doesn't rly have a personality and has absolutely no character development throughout the book. she commits a number of legally and morally inept things in her pursuit of the truth, including catfishing, lying, and breaking and entering. there are a couple times when she thinks about her actions and feels bad that she's doing these things in an attempt to get answers, but eventually she just brushes it off. it would have been nice if she faced some consequences for that and/or learned something about the fatality of keeping harmful secrets, which would have drawn an interesting parallel to andie, the girl whose murder she's trying to solve in the first place.

so yeah maybe considering that^^ point i should lower my rating but idrc

the book was really fun and addicting and super funny. i loved the friendships, and some interactions were really funny and reminded me of my own friends.
there's also an added dimension of race involved with the story -- of how sal, andie's supposed murderer, is indian and how racism affected how he was perceived and depicted by the media and police. it's not super deep or anything, and considering the author's white i didn't expect it to be, but i'm glad it was in there to add a bit more depth to the story.

and RAVI!!!!! I LOVE HIM <333333 his existence alone warrants 5 stars

Title: These Violent Delights (These Violent Delights, #1)
Author: Chloe Gong
My Review:
aaaaaaaaAAAAAAAAAA
i'm having trouble articulating my thoughts so lemme just make a list:

- takes place in 1920s china = asian rep; heavily anti-colonist (as it should be… reading ab this setting and remembering all the foreign countries coming in and dividing up china like they owned the place — which actually happened during this time — made me SO MAD lmao)
- talks about the sexism/racism of the time, including sexism in chinese culture/tradition
- enemies to lovers to enemies to lovers LMAO
- mlm rep and trans rep that was naturally integrated and did not feel forced (i rly like the m/m duo and their interactions and i hope they actually get to get together in the sequel <333)
- marshall is so funny he is my favorite
- there's a disease going around and the foreigners (aka white ppl) don't believe it actually exists; "get vaccinated" flyers lying around.... big COVID moment
- the only part that i was mildly annoyed by is the fact that juliette keeps thinking ab how she and roma used to be together but then has to remind herself that she's supposed to hate him now... go to horny jail BONK
- book seems mildly leaning anti-communist/pro-nationalist and uhhh :=|

TLDR: i like the reimagining of romeo & juliet as two rival gangs in 1920s china. i love the representation and the acknowledgement of the racism and sexism during that time, including within chinese culture. i'm looking forward to seeing how chloe gong continues the retelling of r&j in this setting in the sequel!

technique-wise, this book is pretty bad.

Title: The 7½ Deaths of Evelyn Hardcastle
Author: Stuart Turton
My Review:
fuck this book is SO GOOD. i went into this book having absolutely no idea what it was ab, not even reading the synopsis. so i had absolutely no idea what was going on at first, just like the protagonist. honestly, i kinda recommend that if you enjoy being not knowing things when you read. lol.
this book has so many twists and turns; it doubles back, it loops around. (if you've seen The Good Place, Jeremy Bearimy describes this book perfectly.) so i definitely recommend keeping some brief notes ab the characters.
this book requires 110% of your attention. it moves around so much that it can get quite confusing, but if you keep track of the characters and what's going on, you'll be fine. i think part of what i really enjoyed about this book is how i never seemed to know what was going on, but i wanted to know more nonetheless. i literally stayed up til 4am to finish it. i have no shame.

honestly idk what this review is it's kind of a hot mess.

some other random thoughts i have:
- writing style: i usually don't notice writing unless it's really bad, but in this case, i remember a few times i'd read something and think, "i like that metaphor." stuart turton is clearly a really good writer, and it shows in both his writing style and the book's complicated plot.
- i don't think this is strictly problematic of turton or the book, per se, considering the time the book is supposed to take place and what i assume this is supposed to say about the character (who wasn't rly important to the story so whatever). this was such a small and inconsequential part of the book, but i remember it so distinctly i had to point it out. at one point one of the characters talks about "the orient" and calls asians "orientals". i just--

Title: Tell Me Again How a Crush Should Feel
Author: Sara Farizan
My Review:
*1.5/5

idk man, but i rly did not like this book. there's such superficial and stereotypical bullshit, the writing style is meh (tho it's farizan's second book, so i understand), and there are just some weird lines that are strangely immature. i'm starting to rly hate YA.

the only thing in this book that i don't have super negative feelings ab is the whole thing ab leila being worried ab coming out / feeling like she doesn't fit in bc she's the daughter of persian immigrants. that was valid, understandable, and no doubt based on the author's own experiences. but it was nothing special. imo it could've been deeper and developed more; i felt like that was supposed to be the most important part of the book, but in the end it wasn't rly talked ab that much.

superficial and stereotypical bullshit:
- ashley, bitchy mean girl. omg is this every high school movie/book ever?!?!?! the way her character is depicted is so infuriating. "ashley cackles with the fervor and depth that only a bitch blonde 16-year-old can" (chpt 1 -- sorry no page numbers, i read it on ebook). -- not even subtle. yeah there's this whole thing ab how she's "cool" and a mean girl, aka she's girly, cares ab fashion and wears a lot of makeup, and is slutty. and apparently that means she's rumored to have slept with a teacher, something the main character brings up in her narration several times. like, ofc this is used to make ashley seem like a terrible person when we should rly be worried ab the fact that A TEACHER MIGHT BE SLEEPING WITH HER?? aka rape and pedophilia????
and this line... WHAT THE FUCK. for context, leila is worrying ab being outed, and she says this in her narration: "she would just need to tell one person at school and the rumor would spread faster than ashley's legs in mr. harris's science lab" (chpt 27). like,,, SERIOUSLY?!?!? even in a situation like this, where she's worried ab being outed, she needs to take shots at ashley?!?! like holy shit shut the fuck up man. you have bigger things to worry ab rn besides what ashley is doing with her legs. (not to mention, once again, she's more concerned ab ashley's rumored sluttiness than literal pedophilia.)
also, there's this part that literally so stupid i can't even. she and another character show up to a dance wearing the same dress, and she "runs out of the gym, crying hysterically." like bruh. what???? is this satire? cuz who the fuck reacts like that what the fuck?
- tomas, the epitome of the gay stereotype. does theater, "is giddy to a stereotypical T" (this is a real fucking line from the book btw), and gets befriended by the mean girls. "he was a fun new accessory." -- those are leila's words. and i feel like this whole situation says more ab leila than the mean girls, since they take him in and are friends with him. it's unclear whether it's bc they actually accept him or just want "a fun new accessory", like leila said, and tho it is slightly hinted at the latter, the mean girls' perspective is not something that's developed upon. could've made for more interesting nuance. but leila is super judgmental, saying, "i was happy for him, but i resented the crap out of him" [for being friends with the mean girls]. keep in mind, tomas came out and got bullied and called the f-slur. but the mean girls were nice to him. it's not rly leila's place to judge who tomas is friends with. and let's not forget leila herself isn't out. who's to say she wouldn't do the same thing if she was in tomas's positon?
- leila's whole thing ab being #quirky and not like other girls. i understand the thing ab her not fitting in bc of her race and sexuality, but it's repeatedly emphasized how she doesn't know anything ab fashion and all that bullshit which is so tired, man.

cringy/weirdly immature moments:
- "the ball clocks me in the boobs." bruh. why.
- mc is auditioning for a play and is doing rly well. but "any chance of that happening is gone as i fart loudly. in front of everyone." WHAT THE FUCK
- a child LITERALLY SAYS, AND I QUOTE, "mommy! her boobs are huge!"
- there's this girl who's a furry but for vampires and wears fangs and at one point she "bears her fangs and hisses" at someone. bruh.
- "i feel like i've been punched in the vagina"
- ok this last one is just a badly-written line that made me cringe a lot. "all the women... eat that stuff up like it was tadig, the crispy rice dripping with oil that tastes so good." it's just such a badly-written line idek what to say. so many adjectives and modifiers. why. tadig... the crispy rice... dripping with oil... that tastes so good.

and the last thing is just... one character's personality does a complete 180 with no explanation and it's completely out of left field. makes no sense. could've been expanded on more to make them more nuanced and complex.

tbh the only reason this book didn't get 1 star is bc i was only in agony most of the time i was reading this, as opposed to all of the time. if leila's struggles with her identity had been infuriating/problematic too, then this book for sure would've gotten 1 star.

**edit: after some thinking, i've decided to round down my rating to 1 star, bc now that of think of it, there's nothing positive i can rly say ab this book, more like the parts i didn’t completely hate weren’t as bad as it could’ve been.

Title: I'm Thinking of Ending Things
Author: Iain Reid
My Review:
original review 6/2/20:
this book is confusing af and i need to reread it when i can get a written copy (as opposed to the audiobook, which btw has this part that's creepy af that was fun). reviews i've seen are torn being 5 stars bc "that twist holy shit!!" and 1 stars bc the book is hella confusing. and i agree, this book is hella confusing, which is why i need to reread it, and hopefully things will make more sense. but as i stand right now, ignoring all the stuff that was confusing, i kinda predicted the twist, and it seems to me like a lot of the stuff that was creepy/wtf while i read can be conveniently explained away by the twist.

update reread 6/9/20:
ugh. ok. i’m rly annoyed rn. so i attempted to reread the book to try to make sense of it, but after looking back at the ending, i got about halfway thru my reread before i realized it was pointless. all the stuff i’d found confusing during my first read was now either still confusing, or could be conveniently explained away by the twist. i guess what i’m ab to say it kinda spoiler-y, but it was very much like the “it was all a dream” trope in how you could just dismiss the confusing stuff. because.... you realize... none of it actually fucking matters. and that annoys the fuck out of me. bc ppl were hyping this up as an amazing book but all the stuff i originally found creepy/confusing is now just conveniently meaningless. plus a lot of the conversations the characters were having — particularly jake — just made no sense to me. it was too ~big brain intellectual~ for me. someone who rly liked this book pls tell me why. bc i really don’t see it. the more i think ab how the twist makes everything in this book irrelevant the more annoyed i get. i rly think the only mildly positive thing i can say about this book is that there was this part in the audiobook that was hella creepy and rly cool. but that has more to do with the producers of the audiobook than the book itself. i’m gonna have to give this an annoyed and extremely disappointed 1 star.

Title: Misery
Author: Stephen King
My Review:
this book is called misery, and i was in misery trying to get thru it. i went into it expecting it to be super tense and exciting, but the majority of the book was the opposite. most of the time it's just paul being in pain and wanting drugs and annie being a "crazy bitch." there were a few gruesome parts that i enjoyed for the reaction it elicited from me, but those parts were super minimal in context of the entire book, which overall was quite dull. and the chapters that were excerpts from the book he was writing i more or less just skipped, cuz they didn't rly impact the story and also i fucking hate historical fiction. it was interesting to read ab writing from a writer's perspective tho.

the other thing -- what is with the fucking rape analogies?!?!??! like literally just WHY. besides feeling nothing for most of the book, and occasionally disgust for the gruesome parts, the only other emotion i felt while reading this book was rage. here are the parts i'm referring to.
- paul is getting cpr and the person's breath is nasty af:
"the outrush of breath she had forced into him the way a man might force a part of himself into an unwilling woman" / "and she raped him full of her air again" / "being raped back to life by the woman's stinking breath"
- (no spoilers so i won't give the exact context but just know this is not talking ab literal rape):
"he was lying squarely on top of her like a man who means to commit rape" / "i'm gonna rape you, all right. i'm gonna rape you because all i can do is the worst i can do."
i understand the comparison bc the point is [something] is getting forced into [someone else] against their will, but FOR THE LOVE OF GOD WHY THE FUCK DID HE HAVE TO COMPARE IT TO RAPE. THEY ARE NOT THE SAME THING. FOR FUCK'S SAKE.

Title: Girl Made of Stars
Author: Ashley Herring Blake
My Review:
(i mention stuff that's mentioned in the book description, so i don't consider those spoilers.)

my opinion on this book is mixed. for the first 20-30%, it was sitting at around 2 stars. Mara, the main character, seemed pretty annoying and immature. once we got into the meat of the story, that that stopped being the case, for the most part. though i do think the voice is more immature than i expected. Mara is a senior in high school, but the voice reads more late middle school/early high school. there were some weird instances of "teenspeak," which i found rather cringy, including "craughing emoji" (crying laughing emoji) and one of the characters saying "no big," which apparently is short for "no big deal." like bruh. i hate when authors try to be #relatable by trying to emulate how teenagers talk. because they always do it badly.
another concrete example of the immature voice is when the narrator (Mara) said "the f-word" instead of just "fuck." like...???? what is this, 3rd grade?
and, going back to Mara acting immature, at the beginning of the book you find out Mara just broke up with her best friend/girlfriend, Charlie. and for some reason she doesn't get why Charlie would be ignoring her texts. then, at this party, Mara sees Charlie with another girl and gets upsetti spaghetti. then afterwards, she finds out that one of her other friends, Hannah, was attacked and Charlie and that other girl helped her. but Mara isn't bothered by the fact that her friend was attacked, she's bothered by the fact that that girl was there with to help Hannah and not her. like bruh. BRUH. (also, i was expecting for Mara to get to actually talk to the girl and the reader gets to find out more about her, but no. she's basically just used as a plot device to make Mara jealous and upset.)
there was also this "fake nice"/"faux sweet" mean girl thing going on with one of the other characters, which i thought was really stupid and pissed me the hell off every time i saw the word "saccharinely." of course they become friendly at the end, but that felt really stupid and unnecessary to me. i hate that fake-sweet bullshit.

okay, now onto the stuff i liked. this is a book about sexual assault, and i think it was handled very well. this part of the story was very well done. the nuances in the situation, the difficult choices, how different people might act differently. it was very raw and heart-wrenching. there's one scene with between Alex and Mara that i absolutely loved. juxtaposed and in direct opposition to Owen, it was cathartic.

so, if you want to read a book that talks about sexual assault and does it well, this book definitely does that. but the fact that you have to shovel thru some more annoying stuff to get to it kinda sucks. but i think the latter half of the book over-balances the annoying-ness of the earlier chapters, thus why i'm giving it 4 stars rather than the 3.5 i was tempted to give bc of the first 20-30%.

Author: Kat Cho
Publisher: G.P. Putnam's Sons Books for Young Readers
My Review:
things i liked:
- the friendships and interactions btwn Miyoung, Jihoon, and their other friends
- it was cool to see some of Korean culture and the atmosphere of the country

what i disliked/wished were done better:
the biggest problem i had with this book was overall, it lacked depth. the fantasy element with gumiho and goblins were cool, but i feel like more fantastical elements/creatures could have been introduced to add more layers to the story. Cho only included what she needed for the sake of telling the story, but i feel like it could've been more complex and interesting if there was more. it would've done better for the worldbuilding too. it just feels weird to me that of all things, only gumiho and goblins were mentioned? it's kind of a weird combination. it would've made more sense if it were just gumiho or a bunch of mythical creatures existed.
i liked that Miyoung's problems with her mother was a big contributor to her difficulties in making connections with other ppl, and seeing her work through that. but in the end her mother never being affectionate to her and being literally abusive was brushed off as "everything she does is for you" and that her mother really did love her all along. meanwhile, her mother being cold and withholding important information from her was kind of what caused all their problems to begin with.

so, tldr, this book was interesting and pretty enjoyable and jihoon is my fave, but the story is not as deep as i would've liked.

Title: Pretty Girls
Author: Karin Slaughter
My Review:
CW: violence, gore, sexual assault, torture, mentions of self-harm and suicide

This book is FUCKED. UP. I kinda wish I hadn't read it.... It is terrifying because it talks of horrible things that have and do happen to real women who go missing and the effect it has on their families. This book's biggest strength is how it portrayed the effects of such a tragedy on the victim's family; how they try to cope or change because of it.
When secrets are discovered and the truth starts to unravel, the book becomes pretty addictive, as you want to find out more. The only hindrance to the reader are the occasional passages graphic detail -- this definitely slowed me down because I was worried about what I was going to have to read next.
This story is pretty complex and it takes you on twists and turns, but I applaud Slaughter's execution in how she reveals important details and leaves no loose ends.

As for things that made me dislike the book, Claire, the main protagonist, is quite annoying. She's selfish and inconsiderate of others, and constantly puts her loved ones in danger because she doesn't want to handle things herself. And even after she finds out she can't trust someone, she still finds herself believing what they say as if they're not CLEARLY full of shit.
The vibe in the background is that "rich white suburban housewife" bullshit where the other women (besides the main protagonists, of course....) are bitchy and gossip-y and the main character(s) don't like them. Wow, we love women who hate other women for basic, two-dimensional reasons.
Also... there were a couple random instances of racism just casually thrown in there. I would say that it's to show the Claire might be "subconsciously" racist, since it's supposed to be her perspective, but it was never an overt and important character trait of hers, so... idk. Here are the two instances I noted:
- "her only regret about their sex life was that she couldn't do it wearing a burqa" (ok, this wasn't about claire, but another protag, but still.... what the fuck?)
- "was it racist to assume that rich white people were only robbed by black or Hispanic gang members?" (YES. OBVIOUSLY YES.)

All in all, this book is well-written and well-done, but Claire's kinda stupid and we don't stan racism.

If you're interested in reading a book with a similar concept (thriller about a sister searching for her missing sister) but not as hardcore, I highly recommend Sadie by Courtney Summers! It is not graphic at all (but CW for mentions of pedophilia) and is YA, so it may be more comfortable for those who aren't ready for something this intense. (Also I like Sadie better anyway so....)

Title: Supernova (Renegades, #3)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
*3.5/5
I have my issues with this book. Most of the twists felt pretty obvious, and at times it felt ridiculous to me that the characters hadn't caught on sooner. (There was one I guessed that I don't think was as obvious but pretty epic so I'm glad I got that one right.) I understand there is a certain level of pacing required for the story, but I felt that could have been combated with more subtle foreshadowing.
This book, like I hoped, did explore the complexity of hero vs. villain more closely, but the resolution of the two sides -- particularly how Nova grappled with those two sides of herself -- felt kinda meh to me.
But, like with the other two books, it was a fun time. Though, I have to say: the ending was really cool. And there was one twist I did NOT see coming that had me screaming. That one was wack.
This series would make a great TV show.


edit 1/7/20: after reading the entire series and some thought, i've decided to alter my rating to more accurately reflect my opinion of the quality of the book rather than my enjoyment.

Title: Archenemies (Renegades, #2)
Author: Marissa Meyer
My Review:
*3.5/5

I definitely enjoyed this book enough to get through it very quickly, just like I did with Renegades. There were some things I noticed, however.
- Besides Nova and Adrian, the characters aren't really developed
- The plot is progressing pretty slow -- way slower than I expected (the same can be said about Renegades). Truthfully, I enjoy the book enough while I'm reading to not notice it, but afterwards I realize the entire near 500-page book can be summarized in a couple sentences. What's all that extra fluff? I'm not sure, tbh.
This didn't really affect my enjoyment of the book, which is why I still gave it the rating I did, but it's something others have pointed out that I noticed too.
There were some interesting discussions about superheroes that I liked, which kind of take into consideration the effects superheroes would have if they existed in real life -- normal people become too dependent on heroes doing all the work saving people, so they stop trying to do that themselves. I hope these ideas get developed further in the next book, with how the world stands with regards to it in the end.

Title: I Believe in a Thing Called Love
Author: Maurene Goo
My Review:
I wanted to read this book because the protagonist sounded like someone I could identify with: Asian American, good at school, and bad at dating. I was also interested in the premise, modeling your love life after K-Dramas. Here's something I liked and something I disliked:
Liked: Desi's relationship with her dad. It was so cute! They had a great relationship and Appa gave me mad Asian dad feels.
Disliked: Desi's actions. She's crazy-manipulative to Luca trying to get them into K-Dramatic situations together to try to get him to like her (even though he already clearly likes her, something that her friends pointed out to her) and is even analyzes her manipulative-ness at one point when Luca complains about his ex being manipulative... but she makes the excuse to herself that what she's doing is different... At one point, as the K-Drama Steps describe, she must "make the ultimate sacrifice to prove her love." Risking your future for your high school boyfriend? Definitely a great idea. Tell me how this girl is valedictorian again?
In the end, the book was alright, with an interesting premise, but throughout the book I found myself seriously questioning Desi and her priorities.

Title: So Much I Want to Tell You: Letters to My Little Sister
Author: Anna Akana
My Review: As a young Asian-American woman and someone who wants to grow her YouTube presence, there were definitely things in this book that I needed to hear. Akana talks about creativity, mental health, money, relationships... she talks about being part of the movie industry and being a female leader surrounded by men who don’t want to listen to you; about damaging relationships, and being taken advantage of. This book reminded me of the reality of going after your dreams — in many ways it was a reality check, but also a reminder of the value of working hard and taking careful but assured strides.

Title: Maybe in Another Life
Author: Taylor Jenkins Reid
My Review:
I liked the idea behind the "parallel storylines running concurrently" concept, but story fell kind of short for me. The book was very easy to get through and decently enjoyable, but I found Hannah to be annoying and pretty immature and the plot to be kinda boring.

I feel like the main characters where kind of two-dimensional -- Hannah's impulsive and makes bad decisions, Gabby's "super PC" and is a good friend I guess, Ethan's nice but also lowkey a fuckboy, that guy who's name I forgot is a douche, and Henry is hot and not allowed to date Hannah.

And the cinnamon roll thing? Once or twice would probably have been okay, but I feel like it made an appearance in pretty much every chapter, which I just found unnecessary and repetitive considering it wasn't exactly important to the story.

TLDR: I liked the concept but would have liked a deeper, more complex story, but it was aight so I guess it gets 3 stars from me.

Title: Fangirl
Author: Rainbow Rowell
My Review: I really wanted to like this book. I feel like with the way it started, there was a lot of potential for Cath to grow as a character, but none of that happened. There wasn't really even a plot. Nothing of significance happened. And there wasn't really an ending either. I found it unclear whether Cath actually finished Carry On, which I feel like was her one true goal this entire book. Also, the little excerpts of Simon Snow are really confusing, since we don't know the actually plot of the story. (And it's clearly a Harry Potter rip-off, I died inside when the actors were described to have hair that was "longer than usual" in the fourth movie.) So, all in all, the book just felt very incomplete and half-baked, and I'm honestly very annoyed with the fact that the book started out decent but turned out to be a huge disappointment.
